for any formula_36
Since any Riemannian metric is parallel with respect to its Levi-Civita connection, this shows that the Riemann tensor of any constant-curvature space is also parallel. The Ricci tensor is then given by formula_37 and the scalar curvature is formula_38 In particular, any constant-curvature space is Einstein and has constant scalar curvature.

=== The model examples ===

Given a positive number formula_39 define
* formula_40 to be the standard Riemannian structure
* formula_41 to be the sphere formula_42 with formula_43 given by the pullback of the standard Riemannian structure on formula_44 by the inclusion map formula_45
* formula_46 to be the ball formula_47 with formula_48
In the usual terminology, these Riemannian manifolds are referred to as Euclidean space, the n-sphere, and hyperbolic space. Here, the point is that each is a complete connected smooth Riemannian manifold with constant curvature. To be precise, the Riemannian metric formula_49 has constant curvature 0, the Riemannian metric formula_43 has constant curvature formula_51 and the Riemannian metric formula_52 has constant curvature formula_53

Furthermore, these are the &#x27;universal&#x27; examples in the sense that if formula_54 is a smooth, connected, and simply-connected complete Riemannian manifold with constant curvature, then it is isometric to one of the above examples; the particular example is dictated by the value of the constant curvature of formula_55 according to the constant curvatures of the above examples.

If formula_54 is a smooth and connected complete Riemannian manifold with constant curvature, but is &quot;not&quot; assumed to be simply-connected, then consider the universal covering space formula_57 with the pullback Riemannian metric formula_58 Since formula_59 is, by topological principles, a covering map, the Riemannian manifold formula_60 is locally isometric to formula_61, and so it is a smooth, connected, and simply-connected complete Riemannian manifold with the same constant curvature as formula_62 It must then be isometric one of the above model examples. Note that the deck transformations of the universal cover are isometries relative to the metric formula_58

The study of Riemannian manifolds with constant negative curvature is called hyperbolic geometry.

